Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Lexer State and Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# is indentation-sensitive (#light syntax), so the lexer tracks line and
column for every token. paren/bracket/brace depth counters track grouping
state so indentation rules can be suppressed inside expressions. The
interp_stack slot holds the interpolation mode stack: one 32-byte entry
per interpolated string whose hole is currently being lexed (brace depth
at entry offset 0, paren/bracket depth at 8, verbatim flag at 16, pending
printf-style format spec at 24). A stack - not a flag - because F# holes
may contain further interpolated strings ($"a{ $"b{x}c" }d") and each
nesting level needs its own brace/paren accounting and verbatim rule.
@End Reasoning
Type called "FSharpLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    position as Integer         Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer             Note: Current line number
    column as Integer           Note: Current column number
    length as Integer           Note: Length of source
    indent_stack as Integer     Note: Stack for tracking indentation levels
    current_indent as Integer   Note: Current indentation level
    interp_stack as Integer     Note: Interpolation mode stack (List of entries)
    in_comment as Integer       Note: Flag for comment state
    paren_depth as Integer      Note: Parentheses nesting depth
    bracket_depth as Integer    Note: Bracket nesting depth
    brace_depth as Integer      Note: Brace nesting depth
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Record and Accessors
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A 48-byte token record (6 x i64): type tag at offset 0, lexeme string
handle at offset 8, numeric payload at offset 16, source line at offset
24, source column at offset 32, and the interpolation format-spec string
handle at offset 40 (0 for every token except the interpolated-string
segment tokens that follow a formatted hole). Tokens are heap-allocated
(not arena) because they outlive the lexer: the token list flows through
the parser into the AST value slots and is read by the HIR translator
long after destroy_fsharp_lexer runs. The numeric payload carries the
parsed integer value for integer-family literals, the IEEE-754 binary64
bit pattern for float-family literals, and the Unicode code point for
char literals; it is 0 for every non-literal token.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, value as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a 48-byte token record with type, lexeme, payload, and position

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 48
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-safe type accessor. A null token reads as TOKEN_EOF so that parser
lookahead past the end of the token list uniformly behaves like reading
end-of-file rather than requiring a separate bounds protocol at every
production.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_type" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token type tag (TOKEN_EOF for null tokens)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lexeme accessor: returns the token's cooked text handle. For string
literals this is the decoded content (escapes resolved, quotes stripped);
for identifiers/keywords/operators it is the exact source spelling. Null
tokens return 0 so callers can null-check rather than crash.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_text" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token lexeme string (0 for null tokens)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Numeric payload accessor: parsed integer value, IEEE-754 float bits, or
char code point depending on the token type. The caller is responsible
for interpreting the payload according to get_token_type.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_value" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token numeric payload (0 for null tokens)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Format-spec accessor pair for interpolated-string holes. F# holes carry
optional formatting in two spellings: the printf-style specifier written
in the literal text immediately before the hole (%d{expr}) and the .NET
composite-formatting alignment/format suffix written inside the hole
({expr,alignment:format}). Both are lexed as raw spec text and attached
(see the @Reasoning on read_interp_segment for the segment-mode flag)
to the SEGMENT token that follows the hole (TOKEN_INTERP_STRING_MID, or
the final segment) so the token stream protocol - START, hole tokens,
MID - is unchanged for consumers that ignore formatting. The parser
copies the spec onto the hole expression's AST metadata slot.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_spec" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get the interpolation format-spec string (0 when absent)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 40
End Process

Process called "set_token_spec" takes token as Integer, spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Attach an interpolation format-spec string to a token

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, spec
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Position accessors used by diagnostics so error messages can quote the
source location of the offending token.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_line" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token source line (1-based, 0 for null tokens)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
End Process

Process called "get_token_column" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token source column (1-based, 0 for null tokens)

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexeme Extraction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Extracts the half-open byte range [start_pos, end_pos) of the source
buffer into a freshly heap-allocated NUL-terminated string. Tokens own
stable string handles independent of cursor movement and lexer lifetime.
Defensive clamp: a negative length (reversed bounds) produces the empty
string rather than corrupting memory.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fsharp_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source bytes [start_pos, end_pos) into a new NUL-terminated string

    Let len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If len is less than 0:
        Set len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, start_pos plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, i, ch
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, len, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 96-byte (12 fields x 8 bytes) lexer record. Indent stack and
nesting counters are zero-initialised; they grow during tokenisation as
F# blocks open. source_len is cached so the inner loops do not call
string_length per byte.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_fsharp_lexer" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create F# lexer instance

    Let lexer_size be 96  Note: FSharpLexer: 12 fields x 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0    Note: position starts at 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1   Note: line starts at 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: column starts at 1

    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, source_len

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0   Note: indent_stack = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0   Note: current_indent = 0

    Let interp_stack be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, interp_stack

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 0   Note: in_comment = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 0   Note: paren_depth = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, 0   Note: bracket_depth = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, 0   Note: brace_depth = 0

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-safe destructor: frees the indent stack (if allocated) and then the
lexer record. Token records and their lexemes are NOT freed here because
ownership transferred to the token list consumer at creation time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_fsharp_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy F# lexer and free resources

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    If indent_stack is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with indent_stack
    End If

    Let interp_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    If interp_stack is not equal to 0:
        Let entry_count be proc list_length from List with interp_stack
        Let e be 0
        While e is less than entry_count:
            Let entry be proc list_get from List with interp_stack, e
            If entry is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with entry
            End If
            Set e to e plus 1
        End While
        proc list_destroy from List with interp_stack
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Interpolation Mode Stack
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
One entry per interpolated string whose hole is currently being lexed as
ordinary expression tokens. Entries are 32 bytes: brace depth inside the
hole at offset 0 (so record literals in holes do not terminate the hole
early), paren/bracket depth at offset 8 (so commas and colons inside
parenthesised hole expressions are not mistaken for .NET alignment/format
separators), the verbatim flag at offset 16 (so the continuation segment
after the hole resumes with the correct escape rules), and the pending
printf-style format spec at offset 24 (captured from the literal text
immediately before the hole, delivered on the segment token that follows
the hole). Push happens when a segment ends at a hole; pop happens when
the hole-closing brace (or format-spec suffix) is consumed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "interp_stack_push" takes lexer as Integer, verbatim as Integer, pending_spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Push a fresh hole-context entry onto the interpolation stack

    Let entry be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entry, 0, 0   Note: brace depth
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entry, 8, 0   Note: paren/bracket depth
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entry, 16, verbatim
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entry, 24, pending_spec

    Let interp_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    proc list_append from List with interp_stack, entry
    Return entry
End Process

Process called "interp_stack_top" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get the innermost hole-context entry (0 when no hole is open)

    Let interp_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    If interp_stack is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let entry_count be proc list_length from List with interp_stack
    If entry_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc list_get from List with interp_stack, entry_count minus 1
End Process

Process called "interp_stack_pop" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Remove and return the innermost hole-context entry (caller frees)

    Let interp_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    If interp_stack is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let entry_count be proc list_length from List with interp_stack
    If entry_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let top_index be entry_count minus 1
    Let entry be proc list_get from List with interp_stack, top_index
    proc list_remove from List with interp_stack, top_index
    Return entry
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error recovery: an unterminated or malformed interpolated string must not
leave stale hole contexts behind, otherwise the tokeniser would keep
routing braces into segment reading after the error token. Every interp
error path clears the whole stack.
@End Reasoning
Process called "interp_stack_clear" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Free every hole-context entry and empty the stack

    Let interp_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    If interp_stack is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let entry_count be proc list_length from List with interp_stack
    Let e be 0
    While e is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc list_get from List with interp_stack, e
        If entry is not equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with entry
        End If
        Set e to e plus 1
    End While
    proc list_clear from List with interp_stack
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access and Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the byte at the current position or 0 sentinel at EOF. Centralising
EOF handling here means the recognisers don't replicate length checks.
@End Reasoning
Process called "current_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead helper that does not advance the cursor. Used when distinguishing
multi-character operators (e.g., "<-" vs "<|" vs "<="). Returns 0 at EOF
just like current_char so callers can treat both uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek character at offset from current position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single source-of-truth for cursor advancement and line/column tracking.
Newline (10) increments the line counter and resets column to 1; other
characters increment column. EOF returns 0 without advancing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let current be proc current_char with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position plus 1

    If current is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: column resets to 1

    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, column plus 1
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII letter or underscore classifier; F# identifiers start with letter or
underscore. Unicode identifier characters are out of scope - this lexer
matches the practical subset of F# source we translate from.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_letter" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a letter (for identifiers)

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:  Note: 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If ch is less than or equal to 122: Note: 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII 0-9 classifier. Used as the leading character predicate for number
literals and as the second-or-later character predicate for identifiers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a digit

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex digit classifier: 0-9, A-F, a-f. Accepts both cases per F# syntax;
delegates digit check to is_digit so a single source-of-truth governs
the [0-9] range.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hexadecimal digit

    Let is_dec be proc is_digit with ch
    If is_dec is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:  Note: 'F'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If ch is less than or equal to 102: Note: 'f'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Numeric value of a hex digit byte. Returns -1 for non-hex bytes so escape
decoders can detect malformed \xHH / \uXXXX sequences and fall back to
literal emission instead of mis-decoding.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hex_digit_value" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert hex digit character to its numeric value (-1 if not hex)

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return ch minus 48
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:  Note: 'F'
            Return ch minus 55
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If ch is less than or equal to 102: Note: 'f'
            Return ch minus 87
        End If
    End If

    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Horizontal whitespace only (space, tab, CR). Newline is excluded because
F#'s indentation-sensitive grammar uses newlines as statement boundaries
that must be tokenised separately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_whitespace" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace (except newline)

    If ch is equal to 32:   Note: space
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 9:    Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 13:   Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: UTF-8 Encoding for Decoded Escapes
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Unicode escapes (\uXXXX, \UXXXXXXXX) in F# string and char literals name
code points; cooked lexemes are UTF-8 byte sequences, so the decoder must
encode each code point into 1-4 bytes per the UTF-8 specification. The
arithmetic uses division/modulo by powers of 64 rather than shifts because
the byte-group boundaries of UTF-8 are 6-bit fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "encode_utf8" takes buffer as Integer, offset as Integer, code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Encode a Unicode code point as UTF-8 bytes at buffer+offset; returns byte count

    If code is less than 128:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset, code
        Return 1
    End If

    If code is less than 2048:
        Let b1 be 192 plus (code divided by 64)
        Let b2 be 128 plus (code modulo by 64)
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset, b1
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset plus 1, b2
        Return 2
    End If

    If code is less than 65536:
        Set b1 to 224 plus (code divided by 4096)
        Set b2 to 128 plus ((code divided by 64) modulo by 64)
        Let b3 be 128 plus (code modulo by 64)
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset, b1
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset plus 1, b2
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset plus 2, b3
        Return 3
    End If

    Set b1 to 240 plus (code divided by 262144)
    Set b2 to 128 plus ((code divided by 4096) modulo by 64)
    Set b3 to 128 plus ((code divided by 64) modulo by 64)
    Let b4 be 128 plus (code modulo by 64)
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset, b1
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset plus 1, b2
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset plus 2, b3
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, offset plus 3, b4
    Return 4
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Escape Decoding (String Cooking)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Cooks the content region [start_pos, end_pos) of a regular F# string
literal into a fresh heap string with every escape sequence decoded:
simple escapes (\n \t \r \b \a \f \v \\ \" \' \0), hex escapes (\xHH),
and Unicode escapes (\uXXXX, \UXXXXXXXX) encoded as UTF-8. Malformed
escapes (truncated hex digits) emit the escape character literally so
cooking never fails - the worst input degrades to verbatim bytes, never
to memory corruption. The output buffer is sized end-start+1 which is
always sufficient because every decoded escape is no longer than its
source spelling.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
Untrusted input. All reads are bounds-checked against end_pos; the output
write cursor can never exceed the input length, so the allocation bound
holds for adversarial input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "decode_escapes" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Decode escape sequences in [start_pos, end_pos) into a cooked string

    Let max_len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If max_len is less than 0:
        Set max_len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with max_len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be start_pos
    Let out be 0

    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i

        If ch is equal to 92:  Note: backslash
            Let next_i be i plus 1
            If next_i is less than end_pos:
                Let esc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, next_i
                Let handled be 0

                If esc is equal to 110:  Note: 'n'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 10
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 116:  Note: 't'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 9
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 114:  Note: 'r'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 13
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 98:   Note: 'b'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 8
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 97:   Note: 'a'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 7
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 102:  Note: 'f'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 12
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 118:  Note: 'v'
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 11
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 92:   Note: backslash
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 92
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 34:   Note: double quote
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 34
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 39:   Note: single quote
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 39
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If
                If esc is equal to 48:   Note: '0' NUL escape
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 0
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Set handled to 1
                End If

                If esc is equal to 120:  Note: 'x' - \xHH two hex digits
                    If handled is equal to 0:
                        If i plus 3 is less than end_pos plus 1:
                            Let h1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i plus 2
                            Let h2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i plus 3
                            Let v1 be proc hex_digit_value with h1
                            Let v2 be proc hex_digit_value with h2
                            If v1 is greater than or equal to 0:
                                If v2 is greater than or equal to 0:
                                    Let code be (v1 multiplied by 16) plus v2
                                    Let written be proc encode_utf8 with buffer, out, code
                                    Set out to out plus written
                                    Set i to i plus 4
                                    Set handled to 1
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If esc is equal to 117:  Note: 'u' - \uXXXX four hex digits
                    If handled is equal to 0:
                        If i plus 5 is less than end_pos plus 1:
                            Set code to 0
                            Let valid be 1
                            Let d be 0
                            While d is less than 4:
                                Let hch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i plus 2 plus d
                                Let hv be proc hex_digit_value with hch
                                If hv is less than 0:
                                    Set valid to 0
                                End If
                                Set code to (code multiplied by 16) plus hv
                                Set d to d plus 1
                            End While
                            If valid is equal to 1:
                                Set written to proc encode_utf8 with buffer, out, code
                                Set out to out plus written
                                Set i to i plus 6
                                Set handled to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If esc is equal to 85:   Note: 'U' - \UXXXXXXXX eight hex digits
                    If handled is equal to 0:
                        If i plus 9 is less than end_pos plus 1:
                            Set code to 0
                            Set valid to 1
                            Set d to 0
                            While d is less than 8:
                                Set hch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i plus 2 plus d
                                Set hv to proc hex_digit_value with hch
                                If hv is less than 0:
                                    Set valid to 0
                                End If
                                Set code to (code multiplied by 16) plus hv
                                Set d to d plus 1
                            End While
                            If valid is equal to 1:
                                Set written to proc encode_utf8 with buffer, out, code
                                Set out to out plus written
                                Set i to i plus 10
                                Set handled to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If handled is equal to 0:
                    Note: Unknown or malformed escape - emit the escaped character literally
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, esc
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                End If

            Otherwise:
                Note: Trailing lone backslash at end of content - emit it literally
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 92
                Set out to out plus 1
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If

        Otherwise:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, ch
            Set out to out plus 1
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verbatim string cooking: the only transformation in @"..." content is the
quote-doubling rule ("" inside the literal means one "). Backslashes are
literal bytes. Output is never longer than input so the same sizing bound
as decode_escapes applies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "decode_verbatim" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Cook verbatim string content: "" collapses to ", everything else verbatim

    Let max_len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If max_len is less than 0:
        Set max_len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with max_len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be start_pos
    Let out be 0

    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i

        If ch is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
            Let next_i be i plus 1
            If next_i is less than end_pos:
                Let next_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, next_i
                If next_ch is equal to 34:
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 34
                    Set out to out plus 1
                    Set i to i plus 2
                    Continue
                End If
            End If
        End If

        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, ch
        Set out to out plus 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Numeric Lexeme Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Converts the digit region [start_pos, end_pos) of the source to a signed
64-bit integer in the given base (2, 8, 10, or 16), skipping the '_'
digit separators F# allows. Accumulation is result*base+digit; values
exceeding 64 bits wrap per two's-complement arithmetic, which matches
the bit-pattern semantics .NET integer literals have at the same width.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_integer_lexeme" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer, base as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse digits [start_pos, end_pos) in the given base, skipping underscores

    Let result be 0
    Let i be start_pos

    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i

        If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_' separator
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Let dv be proc hex_digit_value with ch
        If dv is less than 0:
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If
        If dv is greater than or equal to base:
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Set result to (result multiplied by base) plus dv
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Float-family literals must reach string_to_float as clean decimal text:
no '_' separators and no type suffix. This helper copies the numeric
region into a fresh buffer dropping underscores, then delegates to the
canonical string_to_float (compiler/internal/string_utils) which returns
the IEEE-754 binary64 bit pattern.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_float_lexeme" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a float literal region into IEEE-754 bits via string_to_float

    Let max_len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If max_len is less than 0:
        Set max_len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with max_len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be start_pos
    Let out be 0
    While i is less than end_pos:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, i
        If ch is not equal to 95:  Note: drop '_' separators
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, ch
            Set out to out plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, out, 0

    Let bits be proc string_to_float from StringUtils with buffer
    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
    Return bits
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Linear keyword-lookup against the full F# keyword set. Returns 0 for
non-keywords so the caller treats them as identifiers. Each comparison is
O(1) string-equality; the chain is bucketed by nothing because F# code is
identifier-heavy and most lookups miss every arm quickly.
@End Reasoning
@Performance_Hints:
Linear scan O(K) per identifier; K is around 70 F# keywords. If profiling
shows this dominates, switch to a perfect hash on the leading character.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "recognize_keyword" takes identifier as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recognize F# keywords; returns the keyword token type or 0 for plain identifiers

    Let m be proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "let"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LET
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "and"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AND
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "rec"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_REC
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "in"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "match"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_MATCH
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "with"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WITH
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "when"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WHEN
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "function"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FUNCTION
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "fun"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FUN
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "if"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "then"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_THEN
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "else"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "elif"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ELIF
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "try"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TRY
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "finally"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FINALLY
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "failwith"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FAILWITH
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "raise"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_RAISE
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "for"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FOR
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "to"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TO
    End If
    Set m to proc string_equals from StringCore with identifier, "downto"
    If m is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DOWNTO
